{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"ee987e84-1a46-4df8-9adc-81a1eaeb9850","content":"","toolRequests":[{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_01HYxsePAhfbteMmBXZfwDtV","name":"report_intent","arguments":{"intent":"Running tests with crash dumps"},"type":"function"},{"toolCallId":"toolu_vrtx_017j7CJT61UerqDiGAcBnqfh","name":"bash","arguments":{"command":"cd /tmp/sv-feccca4be7fd40bcabce36d0e49c5149 && dotnet test --blame-crash 2>&1","description":"Run dotnet test with --blame-crash","initial_wait":60},"type":"function","intentionSummary":"Run dotnet test with --blame-crash"}],"interactionId":"a9ef90f1-e12f-4e21-9799-7fbc075fd8bb","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user wants to run these tests with `dotnet test` and collect a crash dump if any test crashes the host. \n\nTo collect crash dumps when the test host crashes, the standard approach is to use the `DOTNET_DbgEnableMiniDump` environment variable (or the older `COMPlus_DbgEnableMiniDump`). However, for `dotnet test` specifically, there's a better integrated approach using the `--blame-crash` option which is part of the blame data collector.\n\nThe `--blame-crash` flag tells the test platform to collect a crash dump when the test host unexpectedly exits. \n\nSo I'll use `dotnet test --blame-crash` to run the tests with automatic crash dump collection enabled.","outputTokens":358,"requestId":"0836:2F47F1:C6DA5B:E7BBD8:69EAC5D3"},"id":"9c2480b6-a6e2-4663-8afa-fbceab3ad9b8","timestamp":"2026-04-24T01:22:34.108Z","parentId":"ba4b5566-1b9d-4104-a14a-4576f4fd8307"}
